<font color="#FF0000">VETERANS WHO TRIED</font><br>
<tt>Sun May 25 20:15:36 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
It is interesting to see a forum on Viet Nam and activities in the US during our most unpopular war.  I enlisted in the Navy in 1964 and volunteered for Viet Nam duty every year for my four year enlistment.  I was assigned to San Francisco and Norfolk instead.  I had very many discussions duriong my enlistment with people who had bee to Nam.  I feel that not very many agreed that we should have been there, I also hold to that philosophy.  I began protesting the war in 196and continued to be disgusted by the evening war brought to your by your favorite news station.  I lost a close friend who was a medic, Dallas Padgett.  Dallas was twenty years old where he took five rounds to the head.  Another friend served on river patrol boat duty for five years, he continues to have phyciatric care.  Was it worth it, No.  By the way I am one of the many who elisted because I did not have the education or hope of recieving an education,  I was poor.  The military gave me the chance to recieve an education. <br><br>
In 1967 I was sent to the Canal Zone to attend jungle survival school as part of dive training.  I spent six months in the jungles trying to learn as much as I could about jungle warfare and survival.  I was shocked to learn that the training that I had was not typical.  Good old Uncle Sam did not give this level of training to most individuals assigned for combat duty.  I was discharged in August 1968 and never used the training.  I admire and respect those who served.  I do not have as much right as those who served in Viet Nam to have protesterd, and many did voice their opinions.  I do feel that many of the students did not realize how they were being used by the communists to effect a withdrawal from Viet Nam.<br><br>
It is amazing that Viet Nam has become what we wanted it to be, a powerful democratic country.  The company that I work for is presently involved in designing and building infrastructures in Viet Nam.  What would have happened had we not fought for the oil and other resources of Viet Nain the name of what ever cause was used for justification.  I still do not know if the country was right or the protesters were right.  All I know is that we suffered as a nation and many of us suffered individually.  I am glad that my request for duty in Nam were not ganted, I respect all that served and respect and honor your service and thoughts and hope that all is or will be well.   
<p><code>-- rxnarvae@bechtel.com  (Bob Narvaez) </code><p>


